'''Context-aware services''' is a [[computing technology]] which incorporates information about the current location of a mobile user to provide more relevant services to the user.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/architecture/library/ar-conawserv/index.html?ca=drs-|title=Building a context-aware service architecture|work=Developer Works|publisher=IBM|accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref><ref name="Kapitsaki">{{cite journal|last1=Kapitsaki|first1=Georgia M.|last2=Prezerakos|first2=George N.|last3=Tselikas|first3=Nikolaos D.|last4=Venieris|first4=Iakovos S.|title=Context-aware service engineering: A survey|journal=Journal of Systems and Software|date=August 2009|volume=82|issue=8|pages=1285–1297|doi=10.1016/j.jss.2009.02.026}}</ref><ref name="Truong">{{cite journal|last1=Truong|first1=Hong‐Linh|last2=Dustdar|first2=Schahram|title=A survey on context‐aware web service systems|journal=International Journal of Web Information Systems|date=3 April 2009|volume=5|issue=1|pages=5–31|doi=10.1108/17440080910947295}}</ref><ref name="Baldauf">{{cite journal|last1=Baldauf|first1=Matthias|last2=Dustdar|first2=Schahram|last3=Rosenberg|first3=Florian|title=A survey on context-aware systems|journal=International Journal of Ad Hoc and Ubiquitous Computing|date=2007|volume=2|issue=4|pages=263|doi=10.1504/IJAHUC.2007.014070}}</ref> An example of a context-aware service could be a real-time [[traffic]] update or even a live [[video feed]] of a planned route for a [[motor vehicle]] user. Context can refer to real-world characteristics, such as [[temperature]], [[time]] or [[Location (geography)|location]]. This information can be updated by the user (manually) or from communication with other devices and applications or sensors on the [[mobile device]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}

